16. ostendebatl, “ showed,'' “ promised.'' —ob justitium aut gaudiuml, i.e. because they thought themselves justly relieved from service by the death of the old prince, or else from joy at the accession of a new prince. Aul (“ or else ”) expresses an absolute dis· junction between things which mutually exclude each other, so that only one of them can be taken ; while vel (“or if you wish,” from velle) presents an alternative between things which do not necessa· rily exclude each other, and hence allow an option. — theatra-lium operaruml, ‘⁴ of the theatrical factions,'’ i.e. factions devoted to sus- taining certain actors by applause and hissing their rivals. They often occasioned great disturbance at the theatres, and had to be restrained by severe laws (see 77, and 9: 13).—et quaenam] soret (in the subj. in an indirect question) is omitted here (Intr. 20).

17. Paucioribus tribunisl. There were sixty centurions and six tribunes to a legion, which when full contained sixty centur-ies (originally hundreds=6000), thirty maniples (of two hundred men each), and ten cohorts (originally of six hundred men each).
